1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,340
Consider the same example as earlier,

2

00:00:02,340  -->  00:00:07,240
where we asked if the mean height for all coffee drinkers was greater than 70 inches,

3

00:00:07,240  -->  00:00:11,670
we could again set up our null and alternative hypotheses like this.

4

00:00:11,670  -->  00:00:14,430
A second approach that is commonly done for making

5

00:00:14,430  -->  00:00:17,715
decisions in hypothesis testing is the following.

6

00:00:17,715  -->  00:00:19,980
We assume that the null is true,

7

00:00:19,980  -->  00:00:23,850
and we know what the sampling distribution would look like if we were to

8

00:00:23,850  -->  00:00:28,574
simulate from the closest value under the null to the alternative,

9

00:00:28,574  -->  00:00:30,825
that is, this value of 70.

10

00:00:30,825  -->  00:00:36,720
That's the closest value under this hypothesis to our alternative hypothesis.

11

00:00:36,720  -->  00:00:41,780
We could use the standard deviation of the sampling distribution to determine what

12

00:00:41,780  -->  00:00:47,050
the sampling distribution would look like if it came from the null hypothesis.

13

00:00:47,050  -->  00:00:50,475
We'll simulate from a normal distribution in this case.

14

00:00:50,475  -->  00:00:53,480
I'm going to pull over the code that we used before to

15

00:00:53,480  -->  00:00:56,870
get the standard deviation of our sampling distribution.

16

00:00:56,870  -->  00:01:02,885
The standard deviation of our sampling distribution is equal to 0.2658.

17

00:01:02,885  -->  00:01:09,185
We know that if it came from this null hypothesized value of 70,

18

00:01:09,185  -->  00:01:10,490
what it would look like.

19

00:01:10,490  -->  00:01:12,125
By the central limit theorem,

20

00:01:12,125  -->  00:01:15,145
we know that it would follow a normal distribution.

21

00:01:15,145  -->  00:01:18,800
Now from the numpy documentation on normal distributions,

22

00:01:18,800  -->  00:01:23,060
we see we can simulate draws from the normal using the hypothesized mean at

23

00:01:23,060  -->  00:01:27,745
70 and the standard deviation of our sampling distribution in the following way.

24

00:01:27,745  -->  00:01:33,870
Here the loc tells us that the mean of 70 will go into this value,

25

00:01:33,870  -->  00:01:37,460
and the scale is the standard deviation that we want to use.

26

00:01:37,460  -->  00:01:40,250
That's the standard deviation of our sampling distribution.

27

00:01:40,250  -->  00:01:41,660
We can simulate, say,

28

00:01:41,660  -->  00:01:43,805
10,000 values from that.

29

00:01:43,805  -->  00:01:49,565
Each of the simulated draws here represents a possible mean from the null hypothesis.

30

00:01:49,565  -->  00:01:54,565
We can now ask the question of where the sample mean falls in this distribution.

31

00:01:54,565  -->  00:01:57,590
If we go back and look at what our sample mean was,

32

00:01:57,590  -->  00:02:01,760
we can see that it falls far below this distribution from the null.

33

00:02:01,760  -->  00:02:05,810
If our sample mean were to fall closer to the center value of 70,

34

00:02:05,810  -->  00:02:09,500
it would be a value that we would expect from the null hypothesis.

35

00:02:09,500  -->  00:02:12,410
Therefore, we think the null is more likely to be true.

36

00:02:12,410  -->  00:02:16,145
In this case with our sample means so far out in the tail,

37

00:02:16,145  -->  00:02:22,320
it's far enough that we don't think it probably came from this null hypothesized value.
